C++ compile time 8.35 seconds
===============================================================
Things to Do
===============================================================

1. Critical Bugs

In init_swapchain() – Duplicate deletion lambda
You push the same deletion function twice (drawImage + depthImage). The second one duplicates the drawImage destroy.
→ Leads to double-delete → crash on shutdown.

In RenderText()
You create a staging buffer every frame for text and never destroy it (commented out).
This leaks memory badly.Fix for text (recommended pattern):c

// At top of mainRenderLoop or begin_frame
if (engine->stagingBuffer != VK_NULL_HANDLE) {
    vmaDestroyBuffer(engine->allocator, engine->stagingBuffer, engine->stagingAlloc);
    engine->stagingBuffer = VK_NULL_HANDLE;
}

// ... in RenderText after vkCmdDraw ...
// Do NOT destroy here. Let the frame cleanup handle it.
engine->stagingBuffer = stagingBuffer;
engine->stagingAlloc  = stagingAlloc;

2. Important IssuesDescriptor pool too small in create_main_3d_descriptor_layout_and_set() — maxSets = 1 is dangerous.
You’re using only one descriptor set for everything. This will bite you when you add more.
update_shader_data() always writes to frames[0] in the descriptor write — should be per-frame.
resize_swapchain() calls destroy_image manually but you have create_image() helper — inconsistency.
Many places still use raw VK_CHECK without good error messages.
constexpr bool bUseValidationLayers → make it runtime configurable.

3. Minor / Style IssuesLots of magic numbers (FRAME_OVERLAP, MAX_SWAPCHAIN_IMAGES, etc.) — define them clearly.
Some functions take GameState* but don’t always need it.
destroyVulkanEngine is called howtoCleanupVulkanEngine — rename.
You’re mixing SDL_Log and fprintf — pick one.

Quick Wins (do these today)Fix the double deletion in init_swapchain().
Move staging buffer destruction to begin_frame().
Increase descriptor pool maxSets to at least FRAME_OVERLAP * 4.
Make descriptor writes per-frame (don’t hardcode frames[0]).

===============================================================
Bonus Improvements
===============================================================

You should not be creating a new staging buffer every frame for a simple quad. Consider making one persistent staging buffer for UI text or using a proper transient allocator later.
You can make RenderText() take the staging buffer as a parameter or manage it internally.

1. Add to VulkanEngine struct (in header)cpp

struct VulkanEngine {
    // ... existing fields ...

    // Persistent staging buffer for UI/Text
    VkBuffer       textStagingBuffer = VK_NULL_HANDLE;
    VmaAllocation  textStagingAlloc  = VK_NULL_HANDLE;
    void*          textStagingMapped = nullptr;
    VkDeviceSize   textStagingSize   = 0;   // we'll grow it if needed
};

2. Create the persistent buffer once (in howtoVulkan())Add this near the end of howtoVulkan(), after creating the text pipeline:cpp

// Create persistent staging buffer for text/UI (16KB is plenty for text)
const VkDeviceSize initialStagingSize = 16 * 1024;

VkBufferCreateInfo stagingCI{
    .sType = VK_STRUCTURE_TYPE_BUFFER_CREATE_INFO,
    .size  = initialStagingSize,
    .usage = VK_BUFFER_USAGE_VERTEX_BUFFER_BIT | VK_BUFFER_USAGE_TRANSFER_SRC_BIT
};

VmaAllocationCreateInfo allocCI{
    .flags = VMA_ALLOCATION_CREATE_HOST_ACCESS_SEQUENTIAL_WRITE_BIT |
             VMA_ALLOCATION_CREATE_MAPPED_BIT,
    .usage = VMA_MEMORY_USAGE_AUTO
};

VK_CHECK(vmaCreateBuffer(engine->allocator, &stagingCI, &allocCI,
    &engine->textStagingBuffer,
    &engine->textStagingAlloc,
    nullptr));

vmaMapMemory(engine->allocator, engine->textStagingAlloc, &engine->textStagingMapped);
engine->textStagingSize = initialStagingSize;

SDL_Log("Persistent text staging buffer created (%zu bytes)", initialStagingSize);

3. Updated RenderText() / Text Drawing (Recommended)Replace your current text drawing code with this cleaner version:cpp

void RenderText(VulkanEngine* engine, VkCommandBuffer cmd, FontAtlas* atlas,
                const char* text, float x, float y, float scale, float r, float g, float b)
{
    // For simplicity, assume you have a function that fills vertices
    std::vector<TextVertex> vertices;
    // ... your text->vertices generation code here ...

    if (vertices.empty()) return;

    size_t neededBytes = vertices.size() * sizeof(TextVertex);

    // Optional: grow buffer if needed (rare for text)
    if (neededBytes > engine->textStagingSize) {
        // resize logic (advanced) - skip for now
    }

    // Copy to staging
    memcpy(engine->textStagingMapped, vertices.data(), neededBytes);

    // Bind pipeline + descriptors
    vkCmdBindPipeline(cmd, VK_PIPELINE_BIND_POINT_GRAPHICS, engine->textPipeline);
    vkCmdBindDescriptorSets(cmd, VK_PIPELINE_BIND_POINT_GRAPHICS,
                            engine->textPipelineLayout, 0, 1, &engine->textDescriptorSet, 0, nullptr);

    // Push color
    struct PushColor { float r, g, b, a; } push = { r, g, b, 1.0f };
    vkCmdPushConstants(cmd, engine->textPipelineLayout, VK_SHADER_STAGE_FRAGMENT_BIT,
                       0, sizeof(push), &push);

    // Bind vertex buffer
    VkDeviceSize offset = 0;
    vkCmdBindVertexBuffers(cmd, 0, 1, &engine->textStagingBuffer, &offset);

    vkCmdDraw(cmd, (uint32_t)vertices.size(), 1, 0, 0);
}

4. Cleanup in howtoCleanupVulkanEngine()cpp

if (engine->textStagingBuffer != VK_NULL_HANDLE)
{
    vmaUnmapMemory(engine->allocator, engine->textStagingAlloc);
    vmaDestroyBuffer(engine->allocator, engine->textStagingBuffer, engine->textStagingAlloc);
    engine->textStagingBuffer = VK_NULL_HANDLE;
}

Benefits of this approach:No more destroying buffers while they might still be in use.
Much lower overhead (no per-frame allocation).
Simpler and safer.
Easy to extend later with a proper ring buffer if needed.

