Detailed breakdown of what howtoVulkan() is doing right now (after removing textures)Here’s the current flow, explained line-by-line:cpp

// === 1. Load and upload the two glTF models to GPU ===
gameState->model = load_gltf_model(...);
gameState->room  = load_gltf_model(...);

upload_model_to_gpu(engine, &gameState->model);
upload_model_to_gpu(engine, &gameState->room);

→ This creates GPU vertex + index buffers and stores the handles inside gameState->model.vertexBuffer and gameState->room.vertexBuffer.cpp

// === 2. Create per-frame uniform buffers (ShaderData) ===
for each frame {
    vmaCreateBuffer(...) → shaderDataBuffers
    vkGetBufferDeviceAddress(...)
}

→ One uniform buffer per frame so you can safely update matrices/light/skinning every frame without stalling the GPU.cpp

// === 3. Descriptor Set Layout (only ShaderData now) ===
VkDescriptorSetLayoutBinding bindings[1] = {};
bindings[0].binding = 0;
bindings[0].descriptorType = VK_DESCRIPTOR_TYPE_UNIFORM_BUFFER;
...
vkCreateDescriptorSetLayout(...) → engine->descriptorSetLayoutTex

→ Tells Vulkan: “My shader expects one uniform buffer at binding 0.”cpp

// === 4. Descriptor Pool (only 1 pool size now) ===
VkDescriptorPoolSize poolSizes[1] = {};
poolSizes[0].type = VK_DESCRIPTOR_TYPE_UNIFORM_BUFFER;
poolSizes[0].descriptorCount = FRAME_OVERLAP * 2;

vkCreateDescriptorPool(...)

→ This is the memory pool that will hold your descriptor sets. Only uniform-buffer memory is needed now.cpp

// === 5. Allocate the actual descriptor set ===
vkAllocateDescriptorSets(...) → engine->descriptorSetTex

→ Creates one descriptor set that lives for the entire program.cpp

// === 6. Update the descriptor set (bind the uniform buffer) ===
VkDescriptorBufferInfo shaderDataBufferInfo{ ... };
VkWriteDescriptorSet writeShaderData{ ... };
vkUpdateDescriptorSets(...)   // only 1 write now

→ Connects the GPU buffer you created in step 2 to binding 0 of the descriptor set.cpp

// === 7. Load and compile the shader (Slang → SPIR-V) ===
slang::createGlobalSession(...)
slangSession->loadModuleFromSourceString(...)
slangModule->getTargetCode(...) → SPIR-V blob
vkCreateShaderModule(...) → engine->shaderModule

→ Your shader.slang is compiled into a Vulkan shader module that both models will use.cpp

// === 8. Create Pipeline Layout ===
VkPushConstantRange pushConstantRange{ ... };  // 4 floats for color
VkPipelineLayoutCreateInfo{ .pSetLayouts = &engine->descriptorSetLayoutTex ... }
vkCreatePipelineLayout(...) → engine->pipelineLayout

→ Defines what the pipeline can access: one descriptor set + one push constant.cpp

// === 9. Create the main 3D graphics pipeline ===
vkCreateGraphicsPipelines(...) → engine->graphicsPipeline

→ This is the full render state:Which shader to use
Vertex layout (your 6 attributes)
Depth test, culling, blending, etc.

cpp

// === 10. Font atlas + text pipeline (completely separate) ===
LoadFontAtlas(...)
create_text_descriptor_layout(...)
create_text_pipeline(...)

→ This is a second pipeline used only for 2D text/UI. It has its own descriptor set and layout.Summary of the whole functionhowtoVulkan() = One-time setup that prepares everything the drawHowtoVulkanEngine() function will need every frame.It does not draw anything — it just creates:GPU buffers for your two glTF models
One shared uniform buffer (per frame)
One shared descriptor set + layout
One shared shader + pipeline for 3D models
Separate resources for text rendering

That’s why both models can use the exact same shader and descriptor set — they are designed to share those resources.